12.507 | Essentials of Applied Geophysics | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.507 Essentials of Applied Geophysics | prereq:18.03 instructors:F. D. Morgan, T. A. Herring, B. H. Hager term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: G (Fall) description:Introduces the application of geophysical methods to all aspects of near-surface environmental and engineering geophysics, including the exploration for petroleum, water, and minerals. Topics include seismic, electrical, electromagnetic, ground penetrating radar, magnetics, gravity, rock physics and chemistry, borehole geophysics and the global positioning system (GPS). Uses a quantitative approach to emphasize basic principles and a physical /chemical understanding of each method. Discusses specific illustrative field examples. Lab work is mainly devoted to local field work and equipment preparation for the IAP Field Geophysics class. Students taking graduate version complete additional assignments. Subject meets with 12.214 3-3-6 units
12.510 | Introduction to Seismology | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/earth-atmospheric-and-planetary-sciences/12-510-introduction-to-seismology-spring-2010 | level:Graduate features:Lecture notes, Assignments (no solutions) prereq:18.075 or 18.085 instructors:G. Prieto term:G (Spring) textbook:Introduction to Seismology (Shearer, Peter M.)  description:A basic study in seismology and the utilization of seismic waves for the study of Earth's interior. Introduces techniques necessary for understanding of elastic wave propagation in stratified media and for calculation of synthetic seismograms (WKBJ and mode summation). Ray theory; interpretation of travel times. (e.g., tomography); surface wave dispersion in layered media; Earth's free oscillations; and seismicity, (earthquake locations, magnitude, moment, and source properties).  3-1-8 units
12.511 | Field Geophysics (New) | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.511 Field Geophysics (New) | prereq:none instructors:T. A. Herring, B. H. Hager, F. D. Morgan term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: G (IAP) description:Covers practical methods of modern geophysics, including the global positioning system (GPS), gravity, and magnetics. Field work is conducted in western US and includes intensive 10-day field exercise. Focuses on measurement techniques and their interpretation. Introduces the science of gravity, magnetics, and the GPS. Measures crustal structure, fault motions, tectonic deformations, and the local gravity and magnetic fields. Students perform high-precision measurements and participate in data analysis. Emphasizes principles of geophysical data collection and the relevance of these data for tectonic faulting, crustal structure, and the dynamics of the earthquake cycle. Students taking graduate version complete additional assignments. Subject meets with 12.221 1-4-1 units
12.512 | Field Geophysics Analysis (New) | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.512 Field Geophysics Analysis (New) | prereq:12.511 instructors:T. A. Herring, B. H. Hager, F. D. Morgan term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: G (Spring) description:Focuses on in-depth data analysis and development of skills needed to report results both in writing and orally. Students use data collected in 12.511 to develop written and oral reports of the results, with each student focusing on a different area. For example, students can develop the geophysical modeling or synthesis of the results into other studies in the area. The final written and oral reports are combined into a comprehensive report and presentation of the field camp and its results. Students taking graduate version complete additional assignments. Subject meets with 12.222 2-0-4 units
12.515 | Data and Models | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.515 Data and Models | prereq:18.075 or 18.085 instructors:F. D. Morgan term:G (Spring) description:Surveys a number of methods of inverting data to obtain model parameter estimates. Topics include review of matrix theory and statistics, random and grid-search methods, linear and non-linear least squares, maximum-likelihood estimation, ridge regression, stochastic inversion, sequential estimation, singular value decomposition, solution of large systems, genetic and simulated annealing inversion, regularization, parameter error estimates, and solution uniqueness and resolution. Computer laboratory and algorithm development.  3-0-9 units
