12.860 | Climate Variability and Diagnostics | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.860 Climate Variability and Diagnostics | prereq:permission of instructor instructors:K. Karnauskas term:G (Spring) description:Practical insight into characteristics and mechanisms of climate variability from regional to global scale in the modern world with applications to past and future climates. Major emphasis is placed on the salient features of the mean climate system and their dominant modes of natural variability (e.g., El Nino-Southern Oscillation, North Atlantic Oscillation) as well as observed and projected manifestations of anthropogenic climate change. Learning is driven by exploration of data and supplemented by lectures and published literature. Through inter-active learning students gain experience accessing and analyzing a wide range of gridded data including instrumental, satellite, and reanalysis products as well as IPCC global climate model simulations.  3-0-9 units
12.862 | Coastal Physical Oceanography | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.862 Coastal Physical Oceanography | prereq:12.800 instructors:R. Todd, D. Clark (WHOI) term:Acad Year 2016-2017: G (Fall) Acad Year 2017-2018: Not offered description:Introduction to the dynamics of flow over the continental shelf, nearshore, and estuaries, emphasizing both theory and observations. Content varies somewhat according to student and staff interests. Possible topics include fronts, buoyant plumes, surface and bottom boundary layers, wind-driven upwelling, coastal-trapped waves, internal waves, quasi-steady flows, high-latitude shelf processes, tides, and shelf-open ocean interactions.  3-0-9 units
12.863 | Advanced Topics in Coastal Physical Oceanography | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.863 Advanced Topics in Coastal Physical Oceanography | prereq:12.862 or permission of instructor instructors:Woods Hole Staff term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: G (Spring) description:More specialized topics in the dynamics of flow over the continental shelf, including coastal-trapped waves, wind-driving, and mean flows. Emphasis on the relationship between theory and observations. Instrumentation and the application of statistical techniques also covered.  3-0-6 units
12.866 | Theory of the General Circulation of the Ocean | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.866 Theory of the General Circulation of the Ocean | prereq:12.800 12.801 12.802 instructors:R. X. Huang (WHOI) term:Acad Year 2016-2017: G (Fall) Acad Year 2017-2018: Not offered description:A review of wind-driven circulation, and the development of the baroclinic theory of the wind-driven circulation. Potential vorticity homohenization and the ventilated thermocline. Wind-driven circulation with continuous stratification, subduction/obduction. Equatorial thermocline and its relation to ENSO. Decadal climate variability. Thermohaline circulation and variability. Abyssal circulation. Mixing and energetics of the oceanic general circulation.  3-0-9 units
12.870 | Air-Sea Interaction: Boundary Layers | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.870 Air-Sea Interaction: Boundary Layers | prereq:graduate-level fluid mechanics and a subject on waves or permission of instructor instructors:J. Trowbridge, E. Terray (WHOI) term:Acad Year 2016-2017: G (Fall) Acad Year 2017-2018: Not offered description:Addresses the interaction of the atmosphere and ocean on temporal scales from seconds to days and spatial scales from centimeters to kilometers. Topics include the generation, propagation, and decay of surface waves; the processes by which mass, heat, momentum, and energy are transported vertically within the coupled atmospheric and oceanic boundary layers and across the air-sea interface; and the statistical tools, mathematical models, and observational methods that are used to quantify these processes.  3-0-9 units
12.885 | Science, Politics, and Environmental Policy | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=12.885 Science, Politics, and Environmental Policy | prereq:12.806[j] 12.807 or permission of instructor instructors:S. Solomon, J. Layzer term:G (Fall) description:Examines the role of science in US and international environmental policymaking. Surveys the methods by which scientists learn about the natural world; the treatment of science by experts, advocates, the media, and the public and the way science is used in legislative, administrative and judicial decision making. Through lectures, group discussions, and written essays, students develop a critical understanding of the role of science in environmental policy. Potential case studies include fisheries management, ozone depletion, global warming, smog, and endangered species. Students taking the graduate version complete different assignments. Same subject as 11.373[J] Subject meets with 12.385 3-0-6 units
